.TH BYTESERIAL 2
.SH NAME
byteserial: begeth, begetl, begetvl, beputh, beputl, beputvl, legeth, legetl, legetvl, leputh, leputl, leputvl \- converts integers to bytes, and vice versa, in either byte order
.SH SYNOPSIS
.EX
#include <u.h>
#include <libc.h>
.EE
.PP
.EX
uint	begeth(void *vp)
uint	begetl(void *vp)
uvlong	begetvl(void *vp)
void*	beputh(void *vp, ushort l)
void*	beputl(void *vp, ulong l)
void*	beputvl(void *vp, uvlong l)
.EE
.PP
.EX
uint	legeth(void *vp)
uint	legetl(void *vp)
uvlong	legetvl(void *vp)
void*	leputh(void *vp, ushort l)
void*	leputl(void *vp, ulong l)
void*	leputvl(void *vp, uvlong l)
.EE
.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.I get
functions convert bytes at
.I vp
by shifting bytes and OR-ing them into unsigned integers, which they return.
Host byte order is irrelevant.
The
.B be*
functions assume big-endian (e.g., 68020, MIPS) byte order:
the first byte is the most significant.
The
.B le*
functions assume little-endian (e.g., 386) byte order:
the first byte is the least significant.
.PP
The
.I put
functions do the reverse, converting unsigned integers to bytes at
.I vp
and returning the address of the byte after those generated.
.SH SOURCE
.B /sys/src/libc/port/byteserial.c
.SH SEE ALSO
.IR ip (2)
.SH BUGS
Only the common byte orders are supported.
PDP-11 (a.k.a. middle-endian or German) byte order is not supported.
